   "source": [
    "# Measures of Spread\n",
    "\n",
    "![Measures of Spread](../../assets/measures_of_spread.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Range:** The difference between the highest and lowest values.\n",
    "- **Interquartile Range (IQR):** The range of the middle half of the data.\n",
    "- **Variance:** How spread out the numbers are.\n",
    "- **Standard Deviation:** How much the values typically differ from the mean.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## A. Range\n",
    "\n",
    "The **range** is the difference between the highest and lowest values in a dataset. It provides a simple measure of how spread out the values are.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Formula\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Range} = \\text{Highest value} - \\text{Lowest value} $\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the dataset: 2, 4, 7, 9, 10\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Range} = 10 - 2 = 8 $\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## B. Interquartile Range (IQR)\n",
    "\n",
    "![Interquartile Range](../../assets/interquartile_range.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "The **interquartile range (IQR)** is the range of the middle 50% of the data. It is the difference between the third quartile (Q3) and the first quartile (Q1), providing a measure of variability that is less sensitive to outliers.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Formula\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{IQR} = Q3 - Q1 $\n",
    "\n",
    "### Steps to Calculate IQR:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Sort the dataset** in ascending order.\n",
    "2. **Find Q1 (first quartile)**, the median of the lower half of the dataset.\n",
    "3. **Find Q2 (second quartile)**, the median of the middle half of the dataset. **(Optional)**\n",
    "4. **Find Q3 (third quartile)**, the median of the upper half of the dataset.\n",
    "5. **Calculate IQR**: Subtract Q1 from Q3.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the dataset: 5, 3, 11, 9, 1, 13, 7\n",
    "\n",
    "Ordered dataset: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13\n",
    "\n",
    "Quartiled dataset: 1, <u>3</u>, 5, <u>7</u>, 9, <u>11</u>, 13 (Underscore = divider)\n",
    "\n",
    "$ Q1 = 3 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$ Q2 = 7 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$ Q3 = 11 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{IQR} = Q3 - Q1 = 11 - 3 = 8 $\n",
    "\n",
    "**For an even number of values:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the dataset: 5, 3, 11, 9, 1, 15, 13, 7\n",
    "\n",
    "Ordered dataset: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15\n",
    "\n",
    "Quartiled dataset: 1, 3 | 5, 7 | 9, 11 | 13, 15 (Vertical bar = divider)\n",
    "\n",
    "$ Q1 = \\frac{3 + 5}{2} = 4 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$ Q2 = \\frac{7 + 9}{2} = 8 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$ Q3 = \\frac{11 + 13}{2} = 12 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{IQR} = Q3 - Q1 = 12 - 4 = 8 $\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<hr>\n",
    "\n",
    "**Deviation: The difference between each element from the mean**\n",
    "\n",
    "<hr>\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## C. Variance\n",
    "\n",
    "The **variance** measures the average squared deviation of each number from the mean. It gives an idea of how much the values in a dataset vary from the mean.\n",
    "\n",
    "### **1. Population Variance**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Population variance** is the variance calculated when you have data for the entire population.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Formula\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\sigma^2 = \\frac{\\sum (x_i - \\mu)^2}{N} $\n",
    "\n",
    "=\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Population Variance} = \\frac{Sum\\ of\\ squared\\ differences\\ from\\ the\\ mean}{Number\\ of\\ values} $\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the dataset: 2, 4, 6\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Mean} = \\frac{2 + 4 + 6}{3} = \\frac{12}{3} = 4 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\text{Population Variance}\n",
    "= \\frac{(2 - 4)² + (4 - 4)² + (6 - 4)²}{3}\n",
    "= \\frac{(-2)² + 0² + 2²}{3}\n",
    "= \\frac{4 + 0 + 4}{3}\n",
    "= \\frac{8}{3}\n",
    "≈ 2.67\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "### **2. Sample Variance**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Sample variance** is the variance calculated when you have a sample from the population. It estimates the population variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Formula\n",
    "\n",
    "$ s^2 = \\frac{\\sum (x_i - \\bar{x})^2}{n - 1} $\n",
    "\n",
    "=\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Sample Variance} = \\frac{Sum\\ of\\ squared\\ differences\\ from\\ the\\ mean}{Number\\ of\\ values - 1} $\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the dataset: 2, 4, 6\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Mean} = \\frac{2 + 4 + 6}{3} = \\frac{12}{3} = 4 $\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\text{Sample Variance}\n",
    "= \\frac{(2 - 4)² + (4 - 4)² + (6 - 4)²}{3}\n",
    "= \\frac{(-2)² + 0² + 2²}{3}\n",
    "= \\frac{4 + 0 + 4}{3}\n",
    "= \\frac{8}{3 - 1}\n",
    "= \\frac{8}{2}\n",
    "= 4\n",
    "$\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## D. Standard Deviation\n",
    "\n",
    "The **standard deviation** is the square root of the variance. It provides a measure of the average distance from the mean and is in the same units as the original data.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Formula\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Standard Deviation} = \\sqrt{Variance} $\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the variance: 2.67\n",
    "\n",
    "$ \\text{Standard Deviation} = \\sqrt{2.67} ≈ 1.63 $\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Difference Between Variance and Standard Deviation\n",
    "\n",
    "**Variance** gives you an idea of spread but in squared units (e.g., cm²).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Standard Deviation** gives you an idea of spread in the same units as the original data (e.g., cm), making it easier to understand and interpret.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Variance:** Use this for mathematical convenience and when applying statistical theories and models that require variance in their calculations.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Standard Deviation:** Use this when you need to understand and communicate how spread out the data is around the mean in the same units as the original data.\n"
   ]
  },
